The Russian are unlikely to want to commit a large land army. I doubt that Russia or Syria would be happy for for Turkey to fight a war against ISIS in Syria while being against Assad, especially as the Turkish plan calls for most of the fighting to be done by Sunni rebel groups, supported by Turkey and the US. The US considers the only effective rebel fighting force that could be used against Raqqa are the Kurds, and for the US and Turkey to attack Raqqa (or support Sunni fighters against Raqqa ) requires the cooperation of the Kurds, which Turkey (with its historical animosity towards the Kurds) is not willing to agree to. The US is (presumably) unwilling to commit large numbers of ground troops to attacK Raqqa, and it has no international mandate to invade part of Syria. Like many of the world's (and USA's) problems its easier to say what needs to be done, than to figure out how to go about doing it. I seem to remember we were promised a plan to defeat ISIS within 30 days of the inauguration. That fine tuned machine that is the Trump administration will presumably be presenting the plan very, very soon (or maybe it will remain secret and we will wake up one morning to a Tweet that ISIS is no more).

"Even the United States has had to admit that the Kurdish YPG ‚Äî still the largest component of the Syrian Democratic Forces ‚Äî will, by necessity, play a decisive role in the operation to retake Raqqa. Yet that will pose a significant risk in itself, raising the possibility of inflaming the country's deeply rooted sectarian tensions. This danger has alarmed several U.S. partners, including the United Kingdom, and British Defense Secretary Michael Fallon has warned that Raqqa's Arab population may not welcome a Kurdish invasion" "The ally that could most impede Washington's plans, however, is Turkey. Ankara not only shares London's concerns of rivalries emerging between Arabs and Kurds, but it also holds great hostility toward the Kurdish YPG. Turkey, anxious to avoid relying on or strengthening the Kurds, has instead proposed an alternative: Postpone the Raqqa operation until the coalition gains enough Arab fighters to replace the YPG in the offensive. Turkey has even begun to train Arab fighters on its own side of the Syrian border, and it has promised to actively participate in the operation if the Kurds are excluded from it." and "But Ankara's plan would not be put into practice fast enough for Washington's liking. The United States wants to start the Raqqa operation immediately, and since the Syrian Democratic Forces are the only group ready to do so, the United States appears to be intent on placing the offensive on their shoulders. Turkey's opposition could be problematic, though. Syria's Turkish-backed rebels are already clashing with Kurdish YPG units in northern Aleppo; further conflict, or perhaps a rebel push toward Manbij, could easily distract the Kurds from the Raqqa operation down the road" My thesis is that until Erdogan moves, the US and coalition offensive against Raqqa is on hold. The Turkish army is NATO's second largest but as noted in my last forecast citing Anatolia News; The Turks and their FSA allies are still battling for Mambij. Counter-intuitively one can argue that further YPG moves on Raqqa could be a powerful incentive for Erdogan to act on Raqqa. But to date such action is likely to involve targeting Kurds and forestalling siege of city. Moving Erdogan or ignoring Erdogan are options but impossible to assess now. I will refine number further, as it is a rough estimate for now, but generally the prospects for liberation before June are slim in my view. - Raqqa has roughly 200,000 people (1/3 of Mosul) and probably about 5000 ISIS forces. - Judging by cities like Ramadi, Aleppo etc, the campaign will be a slow battle of attrition. ISIS will be well dug in and will use suicide attacks. It will probably take at least 8-12 weeks to clear the city once an assault begins, even if the operations go well. - The SDF look to be the most likely to take the city. They have been an effective fighting force so far but have not had to clear a major city comparable to Raqqa (I think?). - The political dimension is so complicated that it could cause the operation to be delayed for a number of reasons. Syrian government forces could make a dash to get in on the action, or could simply make an effort to delay an SDF assault (in conjunction with Russia). - Turkey also has a bad relationship with Kurdish groups, and could also make efforts to stop the SDF from capturing a large city. - To be liberated before June, the SDF would need 'all their ducks in a row' - no political snags, and a well planned operation that does not get bogged down like Mosul.

(ISIS knows this, hence today's car bombs in Baghdad.) Even with US military help, recapturing Mosul will require sustained, coordinated effort, which the Iraqis have trouble exerting. Just reuniting the women and children of Fallujah with their husband and sons may tax the system to the stall point, as Shiite militias will have a different view of the process than the central government. In the meantime, Pres. Erdogan finds himself in a truly uncomfortable spot following the Istanbul airport attack. Having looked the other way-- towards the Kurds-- while thousands of wannabe jihadis crossed the Syrian frontier, he effectively entered into a co-dependent relationship with Islamic State. That relationship has started to fray. Adding to his dyspepsia, the U.S. and Russia have differing preferred outcomes in Syria, a situation unlikely to be resolved before, or by the results of, the U.S. presidential election. Creeping chaos is not something he can weather indefinitely. But as a NATO member, his military options are constrained. The Obama administration has made it clear by word and deed that US boots will not be on the ground in Syria (with the exception of special forces). It's certainly possible that domestic political pressure to retaliate could build to the breaking point in the absence of coalition help, but that would put Turkey at the center, not just the front line, of the Syrian civil war until its resolution. A few opening thoughts, while I try to work out what everyone on the ground is thinking. . . Best to ignore the recent resurgence by ISIS forces. There will likely be several more advances and retreats before this battle is done. I think a relatively quick resolution is possible if the factions assaulting the ISIS "capital" actually coordinate their attacks, but that's not going to happen - defeating ISIS is not as important as being proclaimed the victor. And that's perhaps the key here. There is so much political capital at stake in Raqqa. Assad's sovereignty gains some legitimacy if "his" troops retake the city, while victory for the US backed SDF will no doubt embolden claims for an independent Kurdish state in Syria. Adding spice to the mix are the conflicting ambitions of Russia and America. Bottom line: There is plenty of incentive to retake Raqqa before you even begin to factor in its importance to the broader war. It is no accident that ISIS has been so resolute in Raqqa and Mosul, the cities with access to the biggest dams in Syria and Iraq. Whoever controls the water has influence over vast amounts of territory. And, of course, these dams are potential weapons of mass destruction. It may be critical for Raqqa to be taken before Aleppo.
